issue.title: [Bug]: When starting VaM it doesn't load the main menu and jumps to an empty level with unresposible controller buttons
issue.body:
### Operating System

openSUSE Tumbleweed

### OpenXR Runtime

Monado

### Describe the issue.

Preface
---
This issue is a bit complicated to explain because I'm not getting any crashes, I know this is not the correct behavior because when using OpenComposite instead of xrizer it shows the correct menu until it crashes (related issue: https://gitlab.com/znixian/OpenOVR/-/issues/464)

Description
---
The issue mentioned on the issue title happens on the game Virt-a-Mate (https://webdev.virtamate.com/hub_internal/help/get_vam/) the game is only compatible with OpenVR and it's developed on Unity 2018, Valve Index is officially supported and the game is launched through Proton 8.05 in Steam. More detailed explanation in the reproduction steps below:

Logs
---

**~/.local/state/xrizer/xrizer.txt**
- https://gist.github.com/RiQuY/cfcf3514d21b875a1413d14bd14e7ca7

**Proton log**
Steam parameters used: `PROTON_LOG=1 PULSE_LATENCY_MSEC=60 %command% -vrmode OpenVR`
- https://gist.github.com/RiQuY/5fe2d0e548fbf0677006b4ac3bad1d0c

**bindings_knuckles.json**
I attach this file too because the controller buttons are unresponsive and when I tried OpenComposite this file was problematic too.
- https://gist.github.com/RiQuY/99582b5ffe4ff67e4ff446e75035645a

I also have a 60MB proton log file (generated in around 2 minutes) with `WINEDEBUG=+vrclient` enabled in the steam parameters. I provide it too because someone told me that it may be useful to debug the issue, quote: 

> you can run it with WINEDEBUG=+vrclient and it will log all OpenVR calls from the Proton side, then someone can read the log and trace through to see which calls might be failing due to e.g. a stub or a race condition

I needed to upload it to somewhere else other than GitHub Gist or Pastebin because it literally wasn't letting me to upload a 60MB log file.
- https://pomf2.lain.la/f/8slwv1mp.log

System info (from Envision)
---
- Version: 3.1.1-b174fab
- Build time: 2025-05-14T05:27:48+00:00
- Operating system: openSUSE Tumbleweed (Suse)
- Kernel: Linux version 6.14.5-1-default (geeko@buildhost) (gcc (SUSE Linux) 14.2.1 20250430 [revision 3418d740b344e0ba38022f3bed90540ec3de35dd], GNU ld (GNU Binutils; openSUSE Tumbleweed) 2.43.1.20241209-5) #1 SMP PREEMPT_DYNAMIC Sat May  3 07:13:47 UTC 2025 (74808df)
- Session type: wayland
- Desktop: KDE
- CPU: AMD Ryzen 7 1700X Eight-Core Processor
- GPUs: AMD Radeon RX 5700 XT (RADV NAVI10), llvmpipe (LLVM 20.1.4, 256 bits)
- Detected XR Devices: Valve Index, Valve Index
- Steam found: yes

### Steps to reproduce

Reproduction steps
---
The behavior that it is occurring:
- The game skips the main menu and loads in an empty scene, no NPCs.
- A flat menu appears with a loading red icon, the game is **not** frozen.
- You can't interact with anything, the only working actions are moving the head to look and moving the controllers, there are 2 semi transparent balls that tracks the movement of the controllers but pressing buttons does nothing and it never finishes loading leaving you stuck on this endless loading environment.

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/03647e6c-a8ab-42ba-8546-14898004dca0)

Expected behavior
---
The **correct** behavior of the game should be the following:
- The game loads the main menu on start, and it presents you with a flat plane where you selects to load a scene or open the scene manager.
- When you select the a scene (the default for example) the game loads in a empty space with an NPC character in front of you
- If you click the a/b button of the controller it should open a flat menu and let you select different settings or options to modify the behavior of the NPC (that's the main game-play loop)

### Please confirm you have reproduced this on the latest commit.

- [x] I have reproduced this on the latest commit

         task.recurrence = data["recurrence"]
 
 
+def update_task_reminder_enabled(task, data):
+    if "reminder_enabled" in data:
+        task.reminder_enabled = bool(data["reminder_enabled"])  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
+    return None
+
+
+def update_task_reminder_time(task, data):
+    if "reminder_time" in data:
+        rt_str = data["reminder_time"]
+        if rt_str:
+            try:
+                task.reminder_time = datetime.fromisoformat(rt_str)  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
+            except Exception:
+                return "Invalid reminder_time format"
comment.body:
![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)

Using a broad `except Exception` can mask underlying issues. It's better to catch specific exceptions that `datetime.fromisoformat()` can raise, such as `ValueError` or `TypeError`. This makes the error handling more precise and prevents catching unexpected errors.

```python
            except (ValueError, TypeError):
                return "Invalid reminder_time format"
```

> [@Srinivas26k](https://github.com/Srinivas26k) bro still there , any updates

Yes, I'm actively working on the issue. I'm currently focused on adding components and styling while ensuring responsiveness across all device sizes. I'm also making sure that the core functionalities remain intact. Testing is taking a bit of time, as I want to make sure everything is working smoothly. A clean and user-friendly UI/UX will be part of the final commit. Iâ€™ll be raising the PR soon.

![high](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/high-priority.svg)

The current implementation for mapping subtasks filters out any subtasks that do not have an `id`. This means that any new subtasks created in the `TaskForm` UI will be discarded upon submission and not saved to the backend. This is a significant bug from a user's perspective, as their newly added subtasks will silently disappear.

The filter `?.filter((st) => typeof st.id === "number")` should be removed or adjusted to allow for the creation of new subtasks. The backend will also need to be updated to handle the creation of subtasks that are passed without an ID.

         d["start_date"] = task.start_date.isoformat()
     if task.recurrence:

+    # Always include reminder_enabled to give frontend a definitive value

comment.body:
![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)

The use of a broad `except Exception` here can hide unexpected errors. A more robust and explicit way to handle a potentially missing `reminder_enabled` attribute would be to use `getattr`, similar to how `reminder_time` is handled on line 94. This avoids catching unrelated exceptions and makes the code's intent clearer.

```python
    d["reminder_enabled"] = bool(getattr(task, "reminder_enabled", True))
```

The change simplifies the image handling architecture by using a lower-level, cross-platform image representation. - Replaced `UniversalImage` typealias with `CGImage` throughout the codebase - Updated image loading to use `CGImageSource` APIs instead of platform-specific image types - Removed platform-specific image wrapper classes and extensions ### Reviewed Changes Copilot reviewed 13 out of 18 changed files in this pull request and generated 1 comment.
Show a summary per file | File | Description | | ---- | ----------- | | ImageWebService.swift | Updated to return `CGImage` and use `CGImageSource` for image creation | | ImageMockService.swift | Changed mock service to use `CGImage` instead of `UniversalImage` | | BookDetailsViewModel.swift | Updated view model properties to use `CGImage` | | BookDetailsView.swift | Replaced `UniversalImageView` with SwiftUI's `Image` | | UniversalImage.swift | Removed platform-specific image typealias | | UniversalImageView.swift | Removed custom image view wrapper | | UIImage.swift | Removed iOS-specific image extensions | | Bundle.swift | Removed iOS-specific bundle image loading extension | | Multiple test files | Removed tests that depended on `UniversalImage` functionality |

issue.title: Feature: View Images in ICL Repository View
issue.body:
### Is your feature request related to a problem?

Some repositories contain images. These are currently not displayed in the repository view of the Integrated Code Lifecycle.
If you want to view them, you have to clone the repository and open it locally.

### Describe the solution you'd like

I would like the image to be displayed in the repository view like text files (similar to how GitHub or GitLab do it, for example).
